* Generalized maculopapular rash lasting greater than 3 days with
fever greater than 101.0 degrees F (greater than 38.3 deg C) and one
of the following: cough, coryza, or conjunctivitis (2).
** Cases among persons who were exposed and infected outside the
United States (3).
*** Asia, 13 cases: India and Saudi Arabia had 2 each; Armenia,
Bangladesh, China, Indonesia, Pakistan, Thailand, and Yemen had one
each; and 2 persons traveled to more than one country in Southeast
Asia. Europe, 6 cases: Germany and Romania, 2 each; Belgium and
France, one each. North America, 3 cases: Mexico, 3. Africa, 2 cases:
Kenya and Nigeria, one each.
**** U.S.-acquired cases are those in persons infected in the United
States. These cases are subclassified into 4 groups: import linked
(i.e., epidemiologically linked to an imported case); imported virus
(i.e., cases that cannot be linked epidemiologically to an imported
case but for which viral genetic evidence indicates an imported
measles genotype); endemic (i.e., cases for which epidemiologic or
virologic evidence indicates a chain of measles virus transmission
that is continuous for greater than 12 months within the United
States); and unknown source (i.e., all other cases acquired in the
United States for which an epidemiologic or virologic link to
importation or to endemic transmission within the United States
cannot be established after a thorough investigation) (3).
