[The above reports serve to further highlight the importance of
maintaining high vaccination coverages against measles, even in
countries where domestic transmission of measles virus has
theoretically been eliminated. The fact that 76 percent of cases in
the USA during 2005 were unvaccinated is further testimony to this. A
sobering bit of information in the above reports was the observation
that 32 out of 34 cases that occurred in the outbreak associated with
the importation of the measles virus from Romania occurred in a
population that had not been vaccinated due to parental concern about
possible vaccine side-effects. The "side effects" from natural
infection with measles virus include acute encephalitis, delayed
encephalitis (SSPE - subacute sclerosing pan encephalitis), diarrhea
(with severe dehydration), primary measles virus related pneumonia to
mention a few, all associated with significant morbidity and
mortality -- a tradeoff that clearly warrants the preventive
administration of measles vaccine.
The availability of genotyping of measles isolates has further
assisted in the geographic tracing of measles viruses responsible for
individual cases as well as outbreaks. The fact that 95 percent of
the cases confirmed in the USA in 2005 were genetically associated
with importations is an indication that high vaccination levels have
most probably eliminated domestic transmission of the measles virus
in the USA (an effort that began with the measles elimination
initiative back in the late 1970s when this moderator was a medical
epidemiologist in the then Immunization Division at CDC). A pity
that the measles viruses in the 4 U.S.-acquired cases with unknown
sources were not genotyped, to further determine whether these cases
might have been related to importation.
The URL links for the references listed in the MMWR report were
included where available, and are definitely worth reading for those
who are interested in measles. - Mod.MPP]
